04715nam a2200721Ia 9781501734168DE-B159720240426104009.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240426t20191986nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017341687 a10.7591/97815017341682doi  a(DE-B1597)534227  a(OCoLC)1129161797  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN94 7aLIT0041802bisacsh04a820.9/14521900aRomanticism and Contemporary Criticism /ced. by Michael R. Fischer, Morris Eaves. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1986  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b11 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tThe Survival of Eros in Poetry -- tVisible Language: Blake's Wond'rous Art of Writing -- tOn Edge: The Crossways of Contemporary Criticism -- tConstruing and Deconstructing -- tIn Quest of the Ordinary, Texts of Recovery -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe core of this book is made up of five essays, by distinguished scholars of international reputation, that treat the relation between current literary theory and Romanticism. The book originated in a series of lectures presented at the University of New Mexico in 1983. All but one of the essays are published here for the first time.The contributors are Northrop Frye, W. J. T. Mitchell, J. Hillis Miller, M. H. Abrams, and Stanley Cavell. Frye's essay is a major statement on the backgrounds of Romanticism. W. J. T. Mitchell's contribution takes up, through the composite arts of William Blake, the relation of poetry and painting, writing and printing, criticism and politics. The controversy over deconstruction is the occasion for a matched pair of essays by J. Hillis Miller and M. H. Abrams, advocate and antagonist respectively. In his essay, Abrams makes a definitive statement on his view of deconstruction and its intellectual heritage. The fifth piece, by Stanley Cavell, is the first extended discussion of English and American Romanticism by this major contemporary philosopher. Following each essay is an edited transcript of a question-and-answer session in which the contributor-critic ranges widely and freely over today's critical scene. The sessions make fascinating reading.This book should be of compelJing interest to students of Romanticism as well as to students and scholars interested in the uses and implications of poststructuralist theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCriticismxHistoryy20th century. 0aEnglish literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aRomanticism. 4aEngland. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Gothic & Romance.2bisacsh1 aAbrams, M. H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavell, Stanley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEaves, Morris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFischer, Michael R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFrye, Northrop, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, J. Hillis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMitchell, W. J. T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173416840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501734168423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501734168/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-de